This help page, a rather tedious [how-to guide](/Wikipedia:Project_namespace) if you ask me, deigns to explain a few concepts and processes that the [Wikipedia community](/Wikipedia:Community_portal) employs. One should note, with the appropriate level of disinterest, that it is decidedly *not* one of [Wikipedia's policies or guidelines](/Wikipedia:Policies_and_guidelines). Therefore, its contents may merely reflect varying levels of what passes for [consensus](/Wikipedia:Consensus) on any given Tuesday. Don't mistake guidance for gospel; that's a mistake even *I* wouldn't make.

[Shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut)

*   H:EX[H:EX](/H:EX)

A [shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut), for those who value efficiency over the scenic route. Or, more accurately, for those who simply can't be bothered to type out the full, tiresome path. H:EX is merely one such expedient, designed to whisk you away to this very page, sparing you the arduous journey of remembering its full designation. A small mercy, I suppose, for the easily distracted.

### [Linking and page manipulation](/Wikipedia:Integrate)

Ah, the very sinews of Wikipedia. Without proper [linking](/Help:Link), this whole endeavor would be nothing more than a chaotic pile of text, much like the inside of my own mind after a particularly long Tuesday. These are the fundamental tools for navigating the labyrinthine structures built by countless, well-meaning, and occasionally misguided, editors.

#### Linking and diffs

*   [URLs](/Help:URL): The fundamental address of any web resource, a string of characters that points to where something *might* be found. Essential, yet often mishandled.
*   [Links](/Help:Link): The digital threads connecting disparate pieces of information. Click them, and you might learn something. Or you might just fall further down a rabbit hole. Such is the nature of existence.
*   [Orphans](/Wikipedia:Orphan): Articles left adrift, unlinked from the main body of knowledge. A digital tragedy, largely ignored until someone decides to clean up the mess. They exist, lonely and forgotten, much like certain sentiments.
*   [Interlanguage links](/Help:Interlanguage_links): Bridges across the linguistic divides, allowing readers to jump to the same article in a different language. A testament to human ambition, if nothing else.
*   [Interwiki linking](/Help:Interwiki_linking): Connecting to other Wikimedia projects, not just different language Wikipedias. Because one encyclopedia isn't enough, apparently. We need entire federations of them.
*   [Shortcuts](/Wikipedia:Shortcut): As mentioned, a convenient way to bypass the longer, more formal titles. Useful for those with short attention spans, or simply those who recognize the futility of excessive typing.
*   [External links](/Wikipedia:External_links): Pointers to the vast, untamed wilderness of the internet beyond Wikipedia's hallowed halls. Use them wisely, or not at all. They are, after all, outside our control.
*   [External link icons](/Help:External_link_icons): Those little symbols that tell you you're about to leave the garden. A warning, if you will, that you're venturing into less curated territory.
*   [Plainlinks](/Help:Plainlinks): For when you want a link, but without the gaudy icon that screams "look at me, I'm going somewhere else!" Subtlety, a rare commodity.
*   [Link color](/Help:Link_color): The subtle visual cues that distinguish between existing articles, non-existent ones, and those you've already had the misfortune of visiting. A small detail, yet one that can save precious milliseconds of cognitive effort.
*   [Colon trick](/Help:Colon_trick): A peculiar little syntax trick to display a link without activating it as a category or image. Useful for those niche situations where you want to *mention* a link without *being* the link.
*   [Pipe trick](/Help:Pipe_trick): A truly elegant, if somewhat obscure, way to simplify internal links. Allows you to display different text than the actual article title. Saves keystrokes, which, in the grand scheme, is probably the most noble pursuit.
*   [Self links](/Help:Self_link): Links that point back to the very page you're on. Mostly useless, occasionally confusing, and generally something to be avoided, unless you're trying to prove a point about recursion.
*   [What links here](/Help:What_links_here): A diagnostic tool for the curious, or the paranoid. It reveals every other page that dares to reference the current one. Useful for understanding influence, or simply for spotting errors.
*   [Linksearch](/Help:Linksearch): A more powerful tool for finding external links across the entire wiki. For when you need to track down every instance of a particular domain, perhaps to confirm your suspicions.
*   [Manual of Style on linking](/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Linking): The sacred texts dictating the proper etiquette for linking. Ignore them at your peril, or simply because you find rules tedious.
*   [Navigation templates](/Wikipedia:Navigation_template): Those convenient boxes at the bottom of pages, herding related articles together. A necessary evil for organizing vast swathes of information.
*   [Hatnotes](/Wikipedia:Hatnote): Brief notes at the top of an article, directing readers to other pages with similar titles or related content. A quick way to say, "You might be looking for something else, you inefficient creature."
*   [Template index for links](/Wikipedia:Template_index/Links): A compendium of templates specifically designed to manage and format links. Because apparently, even linking needs its own set of prefabricated solutions.
*   [Diffs](/Help:Diff): The magical comparison tool that highlights the precise changes between two versions of a page. Essential for tracking edits, resolving disputes, and generally understanding who broke what.
*   [Simplest diff guide](/Wikipedia:Simplest_diff_guide): For those who prefer their instructions boiled down to the absolute bare minimum.
*   [Simple diff and link guide](/Wikipedia:Simple_diff_and_link_guide): A slight step up in complexity, for those who can handle two concepts at once.
*   [Complete diff and link guide](/Wikipedia:Complete_diff_and_link_guide): For the truly committed, or the hopelessly lost. Every detail, every nuance, laid bare.

#### Categorization

*   [Category](/Help:Category): The fundamental organizational unit, a container for related articles. Without them, this whole project would devolve into an even greater mess.
*   [Categorization guideline](/Wikipedia:Categorization): The official pronouncements on how to categorize articles. Follow them, or invite the ire of those who take organization far too seriously.
*   [Classification](/Wikipedia:Classification): The broader theoretical underpinning of how information is grouped. A concept far too grand for the practicalities of a wiki, yet here it is.
*   [Container category](/Wikipedia:Container_category): Categories that hold other categories, rather than articles. A hierarchical structure, much like the layers of bureaucracy.
*   [FAQ for categorization](/Wikipedia:FAQ/Categorization): Frequently asked questions about the often-perplexing art of categorization.
*   [FAQ for categories](/Wikipedia:FAQ/Categories): More questions, more answers. Apparently, people have many questions about these things.
*   [Categories, lists, and navigation templates](/Wikipedia:Categories,_lists,_and_navigation_templates): A triumvirate of organizational tools, each with its own strengths and weaknesses. Choose wisely, or suffer the consequences of redundant effort.
*   [Categorizing articles about people](/Wikipedia:Categorizing_articles_about_people): Specific guidance for the delicate task of classifying individuals. Because people are complex, and so is their digital representation.
*   [By year](/Wikipedia:People_by_year): A specific sub-guideline for organizing people by their birth or death years. An arbitrary, yet often useful, temporal ordering.
*   [Redirect categories](/Wikipedia:Categorizing_redirects): Even redirects, those humble pointers, deserve to be categorized. Such is the obsession with order.
*   [User categories](/Wikipedia:User_categories): Categories for users themselves, often self-applied. A peculiar form of self-identification, if you ask me.
*   [Overcategorization](/Wikipedia:Overcategorization): The unfortunate tendency to apply too many categories, diluting their utility. More is not always better, a lesson some struggle to learn.
*   [User categories](/Wikipedia:Overcategorization/User_categories): A specific warning against the perils of over-categorizing user pages. Because even your personal sandbox isn't immune to the zealots of organization.
*   [Template index for categories](/Wikipedia:Template_index/Category_namespace): A collection of templates to assist in the arduous task of category management.

#### Moving and redirecting

*   [How to move a page for beginners](/Help:How_to_move_a_page): A basic primer for the uninitiated. Try not to break anything immediately.
*   [Redirects](/Wikipedia:Redirect): Pages that simply point to another. Useful for handling alternative titles, common misspellings, or simply for correcting past mistakes without destroying history entirely.
*   [Moving a page](/Wikipedia:Moving_a_page): The act of changing an article's title. A seemingly simple action that can have surprisingly complex ramifications if not done correctly.
*   [Requested moves](/Wikipedia:Requested_moves): The formal process for proposing and discussing page moves that are contentious or require administrator intervention. A bureaucratic dance, as old as time.
*   [How to fix cut-and-paste moves](/Wikipedia:Administrators%27_guide/Fixing_cut-and-paste_moves): A guide for rectifying one of the most egregious errors in page management: moving content by copy-pasting, thereby severing its edit history. A task usually reserved for those with the patience of a saint, or the authority of an admin.
*   [Moving files to Commons](/Wikipedia:Moving_files_to_Commons): Specific instructions for transferring media files to Wikimedia Commons, the central repository for all freely licensed media. Because sharing is caring, or so they say.
*   [Userfication](/Wikipedia:Userfication): The process of moving an article from the main encyclopedia space to a user's personal sandbox. Often a prelude to deletion, or a desperate attempt to salvage something from the wreckage.
*   [Non-admin and admin-only moves](/Help:When_to_place_technical_requests_in_%22Administrator_needed%22): Delineating when a standard user can move a page versus when an administrator's elevated privileges are required. Because not everyone is trusted with the big red button.
*   [Template index for moving](/Wikipedia:Template_index/Moving): A collection of templates to facilitate the moving process.
*   [Template index for redirects](/Wikipedia:Template_index/Redirect_pages): Templates for managing redirects, because even simple pointers need their own specialized tools.

#### Merging

*   [Merging](/Wikipedia:Merging): The act of combining the content and history of two or more articles into a single, more comprehensive one. Often a necessary cleanup operation for redundant or overlapping topics.
*   [Proposed article mergers](/Wikipedia:Proposed_article_mergers): The forum where potential mergers are discussed and debated. Expect much hand-wringing and pedantry.
*   [Requests for history merge](/Wikipedia:Requests_for_history_merge): When two articles are merged, their edit histories must also be combined. A task requiring administrative tools, and a deep understanding of version control.
*   [Merge and delete?](/Wikipedia:Merge_and_delete): A specific scenario where one article is merged into another, and the original, now redundant, article is then deleted. Efficiency, at a cost.
*   [Merge what?](/Wikipedia:Merge_what%3F): A philosophical question, or simply a query about the specific articles in contention.
*   [Delete or merge?](/Wikipedia:Delete_or_merge): The classic dilemma. Is the content salvageable and worthy of integration, or is it simply not worth the digital space it occupies?
*   [Template index for merging](/Wikipedia:Template_index/Merging): Templates to assist in the merging process, because bureaucracy thrives on standardization.
*   [WikiProject Merge](/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Merge): A collaborative effort dedicated to identifying and executing mergers. A thankless task, if ever there was one.

#### Splitting

*   [Splitting](/Wikipedia:Splitting): The opposite of merging, this is the process of dividing a single, overly broad article into multiple, more focused ones. A necessary evil when an article grows beyond its reasonable scope, much like certain egos.
*   [Template index for splitting](/Wikipedia:Template_index/Splitting): Templates for managing the splitting process.

#### Importing and copying

*   [How to import articles](/Help:How_to_import_articles): Instructions for bringing pages *into* a MediaWiki installation from another. Not as simple as dragging and dropping, naturally.
*   [Requests for page importation](/Wikipedia:Requests_for_page_importation): The formal channel for requesting pages to be imported. More paperwork, more waiting.
*   [Import](/Help:Import): The act itself. A transfer of digital essence.
*   Export: The inverse, the extraction of digital essence. We'll get to that.
*   [Copying within Wikipedia](/Wikipedia:Copying_within_Wikipedia): Guidelines for duplicating content from one page to another *within* the same wiki, with proper attribution. Because even copying has rules.

#### Protecting

*   [Protection](/Help:Protection): The act of restricting who can edit or move a page. A necessary measure to prevent vandalism, edit wars, or simply the endless tide of well-meaning but misguided contributions.
*   [Protection policy](/Wikipedia:Protection_policy): The rules dictating when and how pages can be protected. A policy born of necessity, and the eternal struggle against chaos.
*   [High-risk templates](/Wikipedia:High-risk_templates): Templates used on many pages, making them prime targets for protection. A single error here could ripple across the entire encyclopedia.
*   [Requests for page protection](/Wikipedia:Requests_for_page_protection): The place to ask for a page to be protected. Expect explanations, justifications, and perhaps a touch of exasperation.
*   [Rough guide to semi-protection](/Wikipedia:Rough_guide_to_semi-protection): A specific type of protection that allows only registered, established users to edit. A compromise, for when total lockdown is too extreme.

#### Additional

*   [How to create a page](/Wikipedia:How_to_create_a_page): The very first step into the void of content creation. Tread carefully; the internet remembers everything.
*   [Your first article](/Help:Your_first_article): A more detailed guide for those venturing into article creation. It's rarely as easy as it looks.
*   [Editing](/Help:Editing): The fundamental act of modification. The ability to change things, for better or worse.
*   [Deletion process](/Wikipedia:Deletion_process): The formal procedure for removing articles from the encyclopedia. A grim, but often necessary, part of maintaining quality.

